239. ‘ Oblicus ' with ‘ se verteret.' So ‘sese tulit obvia,' A. 1 314, ‘Infert se saeptus nebula,’ ib. 4393 compare the participle in such ex ressions as ‘ sensit ostis,' A. 11 377. The ordinary grammatical usage attaches an adjective or participle to a noun as its absolute property: here the adjective or participle belongs to the noun only contin· gently on the relation os the noun to the verb. Thus in the present line the order of the signs is oblique not in itself but in reference to its revolution. The principle is the same as in cases of prolepsis.
